column18: Transcribe the written answer of each participant's guess  of the study's goal.
To track how well people listen / take odd requests seriously
To determine how well we follow directions.  Also to compare how well we could use other parts of our body for a taks we would normally use our hands and feet for.
To see how well someone can write / follow instructions with a pen in their mouth.
I have no idea
Measuring coordination when body parts not usually used for tasks are used
If I had to guess, testing how easy it is to transfer from using hands to your mouth for simple tasks

I think that the purpose of this experiment may be to see who can follow and cope with the task. Since it was difficult to keep one facial expression on the entire time, the purpose might alse be to see who can keep it controlled well.
I think the ability of the participant and their understanding/amusement of each cartoon was supposed to have a correlation.
If people might niot find the cartoons funny because they are distracted by the pen being in their mouth.
To see how well you can use your coordination and motor skills. Also if the cartoons made you smile you might hold the pen a little differently which might make it harder? I'm not sure.

I think the purpose of this experiment was to compare how well we write with the pen in our mouth while not smiling vs. while smiling. More importantly we might not process the funny cartoons because we are preoccupied with the pen.
How well people can concentrate: Can people still think well while they ask to do something hard at the same time
Studying motor functions: I think the purpose is to show how much more difficult it is to use other body parts for things.
To see how well we can achieve different psychological tasks.
The purpose of this experiment is to observe how amused people were when they were tasked with rating their amusement while performing a difficult task.
To see how well we can coordinate our bodies to do something we aren't used to and then seeing how it affects our mood.
To see how entertained we are while doing something frustrating
I believe the purpose of this experiment is to see how well people follow diretions given on motor control
To see if we can perform certain tasks In a way that is unorthodox, and see how our cognitive skills (or cognition) are affected when we do these tasks, like writing with your mouth.
Analyze the relation between doing familiar tasks and doing these tasks with different parts of our body. Completed tasks in different ways (physiologically).

To see how we physically react to something. For the first tasks, I did an awful job because I didn't see the point. On the cartoon segment, it was easier for me because I did not only took the matter logically, but I also related to that matter emotionally.

To understand how individuals overcome frustration? It was sometimes frustrating holding the pen and circling and drawing with my mouth. The purpose may be to view if I actually overcame adversity and continued to use the pen in my mouth?
To find the how other parts of the body could be used aside its main function.
To fins if focusing on amusing objects (like cartoons) improves coordination.
coordination between your eyes and mind. You think you want something to happen but you're not used to doing it without your hands.
To see how we performed tasks using different ways of writing, rather than the normal ways.

To how normal body parts can be used for unusual purposes or tasks. It is to see how people adapt to certain challenged like drawing with a pen in their mouth. A unusual task that people are not used to. It is also to test motor abilities.
The purpose of this experiment was to see how well someone does performing a task they normally wouldnt, such as writing with a pen in your mouth instead of using your hand.

To compare motor skills not used in everyday life to those with disabilities. People for the most part dont have to hold a pen in their mouth to write. However, people with disabilites that cant use their hands develope another way to write using methods and moto skills that normally people do not use.
Follow instructions no matter how uncomfortable.
To see how good you are at using different parts of your mouth to complete tasks you're not used to.
Balance
I think the purpose of the experiment is to see how people are able to complete the task in unusal ways
To test writing ability with ones mouth without using one's teeth
Test how people are able to perform a task with a part of their body they do not usually use to complete the task
To view how truthful and or how people respond to an odd and difficult task
The purpose is to see how different body parts can mimic already known procedures from other areas of the brain
First we were tested fpr a motor function that we typically do not use(writing with our mouth) and then we were asked to rate cartoons with this motor function
Finding whether smiling face can effect an understanding of certain things or not
To test how nondisabled people can accomplish tasks with a pen held in their mouth.  Perhaps to test if it has any impact on their ability to recall information/understand concepts.
To see if you can understand/be entertained by something while trying to focus and concentrate on doing something else that is abnormal

ai think the purpose of the experiment is to see how well humans can perform actions differently. We are the most advance society so we must be more coordinated to be able to do things multiple ways then other living things.  I very much enjoyed the study! Also how to multitask both doing and understanding all things humans should be able to accomplish easily
To try to use body parts you don't usually use for certain tasks.
To analyze motor movements
To see the ability of a person when they are doing a normal task but in a different way. Using your mouth to do something is much diffrent than using your hands.
I think it is about how people follow directions. If they do what instructions tell them to do when no one else is in the room-not sure
To see how capable people are of doing normal tasks with abnormal body parts.
How body reacts to something you are not used to doing everyday. To understand how the body reacts when you do something unfamiliar/something you don't do in everyday life.
To determine someone's capability in performing normal tasks in a difficult way the someone is not use to doing.
Attempting to do something out of the norm. Seeing how people do when tasked with unusual things.
Not really sure, possibly how our amusement level affects our motor skills
Testing the ability to do a mundane task with other body parts. To see how well people can adapt to a usually easy task when forced to do it a different way.

I think it was to see whether or not amusemtn affects our bodies to the point where we can not do some simple motor skill properly. Or to see how well we could peform motor skills with different parts of our body that we usualy don't use for them.
To determine the effectiveness of using your mouth to write.
Rate how writing with your mouth can effect a person's humor.

To see how the task someone is performing affects their attitude.  When completing the task by using the pen held by teeth only, the participant is more likely to be discouraged by the results.  Therefore, they will find the cartoons less amusing relfecting a bad attitude.

I believe the purpose of the experiment is to demonstrate how simple tasks we do everyday, such as writing, can be taken for granted.  Some people do not have the ability to do tasks as well as we can and it shows we might not be able to do the things they do.
I think the experiment is about how different stimuli (the cartoons, vowels, & numbers) will activate different parts of your brain, which can affect how well you can do a physical task.
To see how people adapt doing everyday tasks with unusual parts of the body.
To see how each subject responds when having to multitask.  For this, we had to both focus on understanding a cartoon, identifying numbers and vowels as well as writing with our mouth.
To see how people with disabilities use various resources (like holding the pen in their mouth) to complete simple, everyday activities, like drawing a line or looking at cartoons

To see how difficult it is when you are unable to use your hands/To see how difficult using a different part of our body is when trying to perform different tasks. The task of writing and circling should be simple, but when trying to do it by using a different body part makes it extremely difficult.
The purpose of this experiment is to see what people can do with their mouth, and how they use their mouth for different tasks

To see if people can use other parts of their body for tasks they would normally do with a different part of their body/to see how people attempt to use one part of their body to perform a fairly easy task with the typical part
To see if we can always follow the direction of not letting our lips touch the pen even if we had trouble drawing lines or keeping our lips away from the pen while laughing at the cartoons
Showing how we do every-day skills but using a motor part that we don't normally use to completing.

TO gauge the difficulty of writing using one's mouth. TO show the subject how difficult the task is and use their responses to compare to those who actually have to write using their mouths. I dont know.
To determine how doing a trivial task will affect how you interpret something i.e. how amusing I thought the cartoon was.
To further investigate the use of our senses and body parts.
To see how people feel to social media after exposing to a hard task
The researchers are trying to measure ones ability to use their mouth in a finesse way.
To see if you could focus on one task and understand another.
To see how we can use other parts of our body to do tasks they wouldnt normally do.
I think that the purpose of this experiment was to see how well different tasks could be completed using a pen in an unfamiliar way to show adaptibility.

I imagine it was to test people with a dream(?) that affected the use of hands to work(?) to a normal persons ability to see how it changed the (?). The cartoons might have made it more of a challenge to work due to laughter and smiling.
Not being able to use your hand to do simple task such as writing.
Purpose of the study is to determine people's ability to complete task in a way that is not normal for them. I think the study shows how people can adapt.
To see if concentrating on using the pen to write made them less likely to understand things
The point of this experiment may have to do with how likely we were to actually follow
I have no idea. Probably to see if poeple read directions or just skip through them
To see if poeple follow instructions. The purpose of this experiement is to test poeples ability to do common tasks with differing or unuusal parts of the body
I honestly have no idea. It might have something to do with the effect of laughter/humor on muscel control? I have no clue
I have no idea.
The purpose of this experiment is to imitate indivudals who are forced to make physical adjustments as a result of the lack of a certain motor ability.

Not a clue, to follow directions? Maybe if we are able to continually hold the pen, Then it will be easier for us to get the jokes more efficiently. Also it tests our motor skills which are not ine times for the head more mets.
Whether performing a routine task (such as writing) in an unusual way affects someones outlook on comedy or anything else

I think the purpose of this was to demonstrate how challenging it is to perform simple tasks when you have to account for a disability. Also perhaps to be more aware of any frustration shown by the participants
Depending on how amused I was would determine if i would take time to hold the pen. Or test how amused i was while being in an uncomfortable situation
Im  gary larson fan. No clue. Testing dexterity (and improvement?) of body parts that arent usually used
To test how effectively I could emulate that those who are disabled and have to use their mouths to write do this task. As far as looking at the cartoons I do not understand the purpose of that part
I think the purpose of the experiment was to see how well perform tasks with parts of their body they wouldn't typically use.

to see how other parts of the body adapt to unusual activities.  If a person is unable to use their hands to write with, they need to adjust and find a new way to write.  By using my mouth, I was able to use a pen without the use of my hands.  The cartoon part was to see if using my mouth instead of my hands effected my brain processing information.
To see how we react and read instructions.
To test our ability of using our body parts to perform tasks that aren't typically used for those tasks.

To evaluate how people's ability to perform tasks with nontypical body parts is with different tasks.  For example, like people were more successfull duing the task when connecting the numbers because they had to focus on something.

The purpose could be to see how the brain balances the amount of attention it provides to certain tasks, such as holding the pen in your mouth while being reminded of the fact that your teeth aren't allowed to touch the pen, while also trying to do things lke correct consecutive numbers or understand jokes.
I thought the purpose was to test my motor skills.

to see if people follow the directions.  I think the purpose is to see whether or not people are understanding/following directions or if they choose to "cheat" and if they are following directions how difficult it is for them to understand what they are doing or if they are too focused on the pen in the mouth.
The purpose of this experiment was to test and see how well your body can adapt and perform simple motor activities with different parts of the body.
I believe the purpose of this experiment was to see how hard it would be to write/draw things without using your hands and also to determine what amuses an individual.
The purpose of the experiment was to test motor skills and balance as well as self-constraint like resisting to put your lips on the pen.
I believe the purpose of this experiment was to be able to complete a task while using a different part of your body to do so that is not how you normally would do the task.
I think the purpose was to see the feasability of using our mouths to do tasks not normally performed with our mouths.
I'm actually not really sure what this experiment is about. I thought it was about developing technology for disabled people to write, but the addition of the cartoons confused me.

The purpose of this experiment is to determine how well subjects can write without using their hands. Using your mouth makes the subject focus more on the act of writing with a pen and makes it more difficult for them to just rush through the questions.
Motor skills? I think is has something to do with motor skills and smiling? Im not really sure though
To test moto skills and comprehension
To test our ability to see and judge distances without using out hands? That's probably not right
column22: Psych major but working in a business as a consultant

column18: To see the effects of doing tasks unconventionally. To see if a person is more likely to find things comical while performing a silly task.

To find which method is best to allow for choices using the mouth. The purpose  of this experiment was how our ability to choose is affected by how we choose. Our feelings are influenced by the method by which we understand the feeling.
I would say to test for depth perception at close range.
To see how a difficult task can alter our perception on things. If you have fun going in yu will show it or if it is hard then the observed perception will show it too.
To test motor functions not oftenly used.

To test my psychological and physical coordination. I had to think about what the questions were asking me and also how to move the paper and draw the lines. It was very difficult to multitask in this manner (but fun).

To gain info about using and performing tasks in a way you normally wouldn't. The purpose is to use physiological movements to perform taks that you would not normalyl use while also interpreting images in a state that you would not normally be in. The info is used to find out how people think and perform out of the norm.

The purpose of this experiment is to test my psychological and physiocal coordination. I had to think about what the questions were asking me and also how to move the paper and draw lines. It was very difficult to multitask in this manner (but fun).

The purpose of this experiment is to test motor skills of parts of the body that aren't usually being used. Also, they were testing if people find cartoons more amusing with the pen in their mouth because having your mouth in a certain way can [word] laughter easier than others.
The purpose of this experiment, in my opinion, was to see how people perform motor tasks while undergoing unusual circumstances.
To see how well people do ordinary tasks in ways they're not used to doing them (ie writing with your mouth instead of hands)
The purpose is to observe an individuals performance which another body part is tasked with performing a function that is normally carried out by another body part.
The purpose of the experiment was to test if holding a pen in a person's mouth would affect the abilty to get certain tasks done.

To place someone in a situation that is different than they're used to and measure how they perform tasks that may be ordinary if done in the way they normally perform the task such as writing or drawing a straight line.
Really have no idea
To see what my opinion is on doing very random tasks as well as seeing when parts of my brain are strongest.
The experiment is uncomfortable so you can see if the particpant fidgeted iwth the pen or not

I think the purpose of this experiment is to see how well somebody can perform a task with a certain part of their body while doing something with another part of their body that is not critical to the task. In this case, touching your lips to the pen did not have an impact on how well I could write by holding the pen in my mouth. Rather it was the test to see if I could still keep my lips of the pen while focused on writing using my teeth. I think the comics just a distraction to see if that changed when I wasn't thinking about writing using my teeth.
To be able to use other body parts, other than the hands to complete tasks, such as writing, etc,
I have no idea/Maybe to see if there is correlation between sense of humor + how capable someone is to do things differently?

The purpose of this experiment was to determine if we coudl perform tasks usually done with our hands with another body part like our mouth. It was to gage people's ability to still function when put in an uncomfortable situation, like writing with your mouth. It was to test our motor abilities while performing small cognitive test.
Determination ofthe rate of success in the change of the primary modality of writing
To test motor skills, other than that, I have no idea
Actually I have no idea. But I guess it is to test the reflection between our concentration of the different stuff, such as holding the pen and read the cartoon.
The ability about that lip control the pen.

I imagine that the study aims to identify some of the difficulties that may arise for the physically impaired who must write in this way. I would assume, based on the cartoon portion that the study is investigating how peoples' emotions are affected when they are forced to write in this way.
Some sort of sensory experiment. The purpose of this experiment is to test sensory and psychological data.
To see if my focus on holding the pen correctly may have had an effect on my perception of humor
Studying to see if someone can focus on one thing (like keeping pen in mouth) while also drawing their attenti0on to another (like the cartoons)
To see how tasks are done by using a different part of the body that is not normally use, and how we adapt to it.
To test how different tasks and mental stimulation effect motorskills that we're not used to using.
Not Sure. Possibly to see how well people can follow instructions in new and slightly more difficult tasks and to measure their performance.
I believe the purpose of this experiment was to see if saliva was increased when our emotions changed.
To see the way people change their ways/watch them come to a certain conclusioon on how to do a difficult task, and how they adjust to it.
The purpose of this study is to see your ability to write a pen in your mouth and observing the image or tasks that were given.
The purpose of the experiment was to see how amusement changed our ability to use the epen in our mouth.

I think the purpose of this experiment was to see if people get distracted whle trying to keep the pen in the same position.  It could be looking at following directions and completing multiple tasks.

I think the purpose of this experiment is to test our reactions to weird cartoons and how much effort we put into trying our hardest to circle in the answer/response and also to connect/underline the appropriate answer.
I have no idea.
To measure frustration due to inability to do what you want to do

I think that you may be examining if different motions, or how happy we are, is correlated with different muscles in the face. If we were more amused, does that mean we were able to circle the number better? I think you could also analyze the different strategies used to complete the tasks. Different people may have had a different way of doing it
To see how well people can do things with body parts they don't usually use to do said things
To test our ability to write with our mouth instead of our hands. I think the cartoons were trying to see if it was easier or harder depending on if we thought the cartoon was funny.
Test coordination relative to optical perception using motor skills not normally used. Most likely to see how well the human mind & body can adapt to new situations using different motor skills
I believe that the purpose of this experiment is to see if feelings or thoughts reflect motor skills
I think it may be to monitor facial muscle movements
The purpose of this experiment is to determine how much control of the outcome people have when utilizing utencils in unfamiliar places

Test how well you can understand while using other parts of body. Testing the ability to think while writing with a diff part of the body. The ability to think straight while holding a writing instrument in an unorthodox manner obviously impairs thinking ability to some degree unless you are experienced in writing in that position.
Test how we can process/find humor in normal things when completing abnormal tasks
I think the purpose was to see how good people are at following challenging instructions. Also how using a pen in this disadvantaged way affects our mood.
How well participants follow instruction, to determine how well people follow rules and instruction when an authority figure is not present
To test how easy is it is for a person to do a task they are not used to
Whether I'd follow directions? I was given a task of skills that were somewhat a challenge to complete. I'm guessing the mbean (??) was used to follow if I didn't cheat
